<h2> Introduction:</h2>

This lab provides experience with stream file I/O.<br>

<h2> Lab Assignment:</h2>

<h4> Problem Motivation and Definition:</h4>

The stream flags and operators apply to more than just the four standard files.
<br>(<tt>cout, cin, cerr, clog</tt>)<br>
They apply to any file you can name.

<h4> Solution Specification:</h4>
<ol>
    <li> Create a new directory, <tt>lab9</tt>, and move to it.

    <li> Perform Programming Project 12.19

    <ol>
	<li>Use the &lt;tt&gt; font for the program characters.
	<li>The HTML title should be the name of the program.
	<li>Transform other characters valid in C++ programs which have 
	    special meanings in HTML.
	<li>Number the statements consecutively from 1 in a field six characters wide.
	<li>Append the program's output to the source code (in the style of the
	<b>Demo Code</b> on our course Website).<br>
	{Note: <i>this must be done within the HTML body</i>}
	<li>Use the command line to enter
	the program to transform, it's output to append, and the resultant HTML file.
    </ol>

    <li> When correct, generate via <tt>enscript</tt> an HTML printout of the
    sources, and demonstrate, via <tt>script</tt>, the sources and the
    running of the program data.<br>
    Submit to D2L.
</ol>

